BM25-llava_documents.content: This graph displays the public awareness of a number of Grammy Award nominees before the 2014 Grammy Awards were held, shown as a pecentage of those interviewed who indicated having heard about a certain artist or band. Veteran musician David Bowie received an awareness rating of 78 percent, 32 percent more than reported having heard about breakthrough artists Macklemore & Ryan Lewis. Newcomer Lorde had only a 33 percent awareness rating before the Grammy Awards, but nonetheless received two Grammy Awards, including the coveted "Song of the Year" award.
BM25-llava_documents.title: Public awareness ratings of Grammy Award nominees as of January 2014

BM25-llava_documents.content: President Obama’s job approval has ticked up in recent months, to 48% currently, and his rating dwarfs the 26% approval measure for the leaders of the new Republican Congress. Yet the public is divided over whether Obama or Republican congressional leaders should take the lead in solving the nation’s problems: 40% say Obama while 38% say GOP leaders. That is virtually unchanged from a few days after the midterm elections in November.  The latest national survey by the Pew Research Center, conducted Feb. 18-22, 2015 among 1,504 adults, finds that both parties are viewed by majorities as having strong principles. Somewhat more say this about the GOP (63%) than the Democratic Party (57%).
BM25-llava_documents.title: Public Divided Over ‘Who Should Take the Lead’

BM25_documents.content: As of December 2020, about 39 percent of Americans approved of the way Donald Trump was handling his job as president. President Trump’s public approval has been consistently fluctuating since he assumed office in January 2017. Approval of Administration Donald Trump’s presidency has caused a lot of controversy and debate both within and outside the United States. It took only eight days from his first day in office for Donald Trump to receive over a 51 percent disapproval rating. The President is not the only politician with low approval ratings, as many Senators also face low approval ratings. However, President Trump’s approval ratings are not much lower than the approval rating of former president Barack Obama after the same amount of time in office. Political Issues Trump’s popularity varies among ages, gender, race, and political parties. However, Republicans believe that President Trump’s treatment in the media was very unfair. The President’s handling of the COVID-19 pandemic and George Floyd protests have caused controversy in the United States and created a significant political divide among the two major parties. In his race for reelection, President Trump trails behind Democratic challenger Joe Biden in national polling.
BM25_documents.title: Do you approve or disapprove of the way Donald Trump is handling his job as president?

Clip_documents.content: After shrinking in 2009, during the global recession, Mexico’s economy rebounded impressively in 2010 – growing at its fastest rate in a decade. Still, an overwhelming majority of Mexicans remain dissatisfied with economic conditions and with their nation’s direction overall. Roughly three-quarters (76%) say they are unhappy with the way things are going in their country, little changed from assessments in 2009 and 2010. Dissatisfaction with the country’s direction is common across the different regions of Mexico and cuts across income and educational levels.
Clip_documents.title: Dissatisfaction Direction With

Clip_documents.content: Overall, a majority (56%) say they are satisfied with the results of the election, compared with a third (33%) who are dissatisfied. One-in-ten do not have an opinion either way.
Clip_documents.title: Most Satisfied with

Clip_documents.content: Overall, the Japanese public is decidedly pessimistic about how things are going in their country. Fully 78% express dissatisfaction with the country’s direction, while an overwhelming 93% describe the current state of the economy as bad. Compared with last year, fewer expect the economic situation to worsen, but the prevailing view is that the economy will stagnate, rather than improve in the months ahead.
Clip_documents.title: Most Dissatisfied

Mistral-llava_documents.content: In the high-stakes battle over replacing Justice Antonin Scalia on the Supreme Court, a majority of Americans (56%) say the Senate should hold hearings and vote on President Obama’s choice to fill the vacancy. About four-in-ten (38%) say the Senate should not hold hearings until the next president selects a court nominee.  Most of those who want the Senate to hold off consideration of a Supreme Court nominee say they would not change their minds about this, regardless of whom Obama selects to replace Scalia. About a quarter of the public (26%) favors the Senate delaying action on the court vacancy, and say they would not be swayed from this view no matter whom Obama nominates. Just 10% of the public favors holding off action on the court vacancy, but say they may change their minds, depending on whom Obama nominates.
Mistral-llava_documents.title: 2-22-2016 2-55-29 PM
